<br>
At least some portion of the people who obtain pirated material may have bought it otherwise.  It still affects their bottom line, even though it isn't comparable on a 1 for 1 basis. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=syllestraefv>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3560<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/26/03 1:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=688.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pirates, etc.</span><hr size=1> CD prices started around 15 bucks, then dipped to around 10 bucks for new CDs, then went back up to 15 again (this is where the price fixing charges were levied).<br>
<br>
Today, most new CDs I see cost about 18 bucks, or 15 on sale.<br>
<br>
The cost of putting the music onto a CD has gotten lower over the years, as technology has improved.<br>
<br>
The cost <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>should</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have dropped to be, at least, similar with what is charged for cassette tapes.  That hasn't happened.<br>
<br>
What the recording industry is finding is that there are a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>lot</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of people who want to buy music, but not at the prices they charge.  What they should do is lower prices to appeal to a much wider audience.  Instead they're pushing prices higher trying to claim victimization by download sites.  <br>
<br>
As prices are pushed higher, more people become interested in stealing music, and they drive even more people to file-share sites.<br>
<br>
While I don't have any sympathy for those that steal (as opposed to those who just boycott period).  But likewise I have no sympathy for the recording industry either.  They're creating their own problems.<br>
<br>
