And this is certainly true.  Not everyone who pirates would have purchased the item in question had it not been available through the unique alternative acquisition process the Internet has become.  However, it's really sort of a moot point once it is pirated, because they no longer have to worry about whether or not they would have bought it.  Once you have it sitting on your hard drive, it is trivial to say &quot;Oh, this?  I never would have actually *bought* it.  Really, it was barely worth the trouble to download.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=syllestraefv>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3562<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/26/03 1:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=688.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pirates, etc.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If I was illegally distrubting Microsoft Office online, how fast do you think I would be shut down?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
