<br>
In the end, our opinions on the matter may not matter very much.  At some point there is going to be a system developed that garantees 100% anonymity of the users of p2p software. <br>
<br>
The most promising thing at the moment to realizing this goal is Wi-Fi enabled laptops along with &quot;wireless clouds&quot; that are already being implemented in many of the larger cities in the U.S. today.<br>
<br>
Now, with the promise of total online privacy on the horizon I would hazard a guess that the RIAA is in a heap of trouble, no matter what they do legally.  The courts have already set precedent in case law that ISPs are not to blame for what their users do.<br>
<br>
As a matter of fact, the reason we are seeing this wave of mass suings is because of this precedent, and another in which an ISP (verizon) was forced to hand over user information to the RIAA, via a subpeona, with out need of a warrant.<br>
<br>
You can rant all you like about theft and such, but  you are setting a moral double standard by which one party is required to behave honorably, while the other is free to gouge and sceem and lie at will.  Because it has the law on it's side.<br>
<br>
But here's an ethics question that would have been right at home in my last ethics class: Are we to follow the laws that men make, be they just or not, or shall we follow a higher moral law, a law governered only by the conscience, that must take precedence over unjust laws?<br>
<br>
And here's the rub of it. If not for the laws the RIAA has directly and tracebly paid to have enacted over the past several years, by giving away large sums of money to politicians with little or no conscience downloading whatever you like would still be perfectly safe and somewhat legal.<br>
<br>
Now, lets see I disagree with a few of the premises the RIAA has set forth.<br>
<br>
They say the own the copywrites. Fine, they do.  I don't care.  I have far more respect for the artists and songwriters that colluded to produce the art that they made than some bean counters and fat middle aged record executives who control the ONLY means of distributing music to the mass market and so force these poor artists in to ruinous contracts.  I have downloaded music before.  I have paid some artists directly before if I especially like it.  As far as record execs go though? fuck them.  I hope they fucking starve to death in the streets.  You ought to read some of the contracts these poor artist's sign.  It's fucking indentured servitude.<br>
<br>
Yeah, I like some of their music.  Yeah, I download it and listen to it.  If I like it enough I'll find a way to pay the artist.  My passionate hatred of the industry isn't going to stop me appreciating some of it's artists.  And I will show my appreciation in turn.  To those that deserve it.  <br>
<br>
