<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So, I have actually given a second argument here, in addition to my earlier one, which proved that supporting p2p is morally superior to not. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You have proved absolutely nothing except that you have no moral basis to stand on.  All you've done is babble about how technology and piracy is going to drive the RIAA out of business.  And, actually, you've provided absolutely NO factual evidence to support that assertion.  Just a bunch of hearsay, hyperbole and nonsense wrapped up in a bunch of fancy words, half of which you don't even know how to spell.<br>
<br>
I am not defending the actions of the RIAA.  I agree that there are a lot of problems with the industry as a whole and that there will be significant changes in the way music is distributed in the future.  But your assertions about p2p piracy being some sort of &quot;Adam Smith's Invisible Hand&quot; is about as baseless as the moral ground on which you stand.  Although software piracy is significant, it is still a relatively small portion of the total market for music.  Maybe you'd better go back to Econ 101 and learn a little more about supply, demand and price.  And no matter how fast you think technology is going to find ways to hide you, there will be technology developed just as fast to find you.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Behavioristic psychology and psychoanalysis have always upheld the Philistine view that fine moral words are one thing and moral deeds another. Morally mature reasoning is quite a different matter, and does not really depend on &quot;fine words.&quot; The man who understands justice is more likely to practice it. -- Lawrence Kohlberg<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
